<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<object type="traktor.mcp.SkillAsset">
	<name>traktor-lua-scripting</name>
	<description>Idioms and gotchas for authoring traktor LUA Stage scripts (namespace import, direct type references, #using, Stage lifecycle).</description>
	<whenToUse><![CDATA[Writing or editing a LUA Stage/script in traktor (e.g. Scripts/Main), or wiring entity/component logic from script.]]></whenToUse>
	<body><![CDATA[# Authoring traktor LUA scripts

Conventions and gotchas for writing a LUA `Stage` script (e.g. `Scripts/Main`). These are style/idiom rules, not a task — apply them whenever you author or edit a script.

## Namespace import
- Put `import(traktor)` at the top of the script (after the `#using` directives). It pulls the `traktor` namespace's types into local scope, so you write `Vector4`, `Quaternion`, `Transform`, `TypeInfo`, … instead of `traktor.Vector4`, etc.
- Only the **top-level** `traktor.*` types are flattened. Types in a sub-namespace are still referenced by their full path, e.g. `traktor.physics.CharacterComponent`, `traktor.animation.SkeletonComponent`.

## Reference types directly — don't look them up by string
- Where an API wants a type (e.g. `entity:getComponent(...)`), pass the **type itself**; it auto-boxes into a `BoxedType`:
  - `entity:getComponent(traktor.physics.CharacterComponent)`
  - `entity:getComponent(traktor.animation.SkeletonComponent)`
- Avoid the string-lookup form `getComponent(TypeInfo.find("traktor.physics.CharacterComponent"))` — it is verbose, unchecked (a typo'd string fails silently at runtime), and unnecessary.
- Reserve type-name **strings** for cases that genuinely need a string identifier, not for resolving a type you can name directly.

## `#using` dependencies
- `#using \{<guid>}` includes another script/asset (e.g. the `Stage` base class, UiKit widgets) so its symbols are available. List one per dependency at the very top, before `import(traktor)`.

## Stage lifecycle (the common script shape)
- Declare the class idempotently: `Main = Main or class("Main", Stage)`.
- `function Main:new(params, environment)` — call `Stage.new(self, params, environment)` first, then set up UI/state.
- `function Main:finalize()` — tear down what `new` created (remove frames, nil references).
- `function Main:update(info)` — per-frame; `info.simulationTime`, `info.frameDeltaTime`.
- Resolve world entities lazily and cache them: `local world = self.world.world` (may be nil early); `world:getEntity("Name")`; guard every lookup with a nil check and only cache once found.

## Gotchas
- `world` (`self.world.world`) can be nil for the first frames — bail out of `update` cleanly until it resolves.
- Drive an animation state graph with `poseController:setParameterValue(name, value)`; `setState(...)` is a no-op stub.
- `CharacterComponent:move(velocity, vertical)` — pass `false` for horizontal locomotion; the controller applies gravity itself. Set body yaw via `headAngle`, and don't also write the entity rotation from script.
]]></body>
	<engineVersion/>
	<published>false</published>
